> On 11/05/2012 05:34 PM, Bill Dube wrote:
>
> > It is an overly-simplistic explanation, but it is useful think of
> > the brush advance being needed because of the inductance of the
> > armature windings. As the motor spins faster, and/or with larger
> > current, you need to begin ramping up the armature winding current
> > a bit sooner, and ramping it down a bit sooner too, to keep the
> > armature field properly aligned with the field poles. Advancing
> > the brush timing accomplishes this.
> >
> > Somewhat analogous to advancing the spark timing in a gasoline
> > engine. You have to touch off the combustion earlier as the engine
> > spins faster to make up for the delay in flame travel.
>
> Perhaps this question will show my complete ignorance...but has
> anybody tried to rig up some mechanical system to dynamically change
> the brush advance "on the fly"? Any real advantages to doing that?
> (other than being able to reverse a motor without lots of sparks?)
>
> Jay
